# Review of `app.js` — Error Handling, Input Validation & Security

The file is very small (23 lines) with only two endpoints, but there's still quite a bit missing from a security/robustness perspective. Here are concrete suggestions:

## 1. Missing Global Error Handling
There's no error-handling middleware. Uncaught errors in Express handlers will leak stack traces in development mode and may crash the process.

```js
// Add at the bottom, after all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
});

// Handle unknown routes
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' }));

// Process-level safety nets
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => console.error('Unhandled rejection:', reason));
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => { console.error('Uncaught exception:', err); process.exit(1); });
```

## 2. No Body Parsing Limits
Once you accept POST/PUT bodies, set explicit size caps to prevent DoS:
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

## 3. No Security Headers
Add `helmet` to set sane defaults (CSP, X-Frame-Options, HSTS, etc.):
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

## 4. No Rate Limiting
Both endpoints are open to abuse:
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

## 5. CORS Not Configured
If this will be hit by browsers, explicitly configure CORS with an allowlist rather than leaving it default/open:
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://yourdomain.com'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

## 6. Input Validation (when endpoints grow)
Neither route currently takes input, but when `/users/:id` or query params get added, validate strictly. Use a schema library:
```js
const { z } = require('zod');
const idSchema = z.coerce.number().int().positive();

app.get('/users/:id', (req, res, next) => {
  const parsed = idSchema.safeParse(req.params.id);
  if (!parsed.success) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid id' });
  // ... lookup
});
```
Key principles: whitelist, not blacklist; coerce types explicitly; reject on failure with 400.

## 7. Sensitive Data Exposure in `/users`
`/users` returns email addresses with no authentication. Even as sample data, this models a bad pattern. Require auth and return only fields the caller is authorized to see:
```js
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  res.json(users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name }))); // omit email unless needed
});
```

## 8. Hardcoded Port & No Graceful Shutdown
```js
const port = process.env.PORT || 3000;
const server = app.listen(port, () => console.log(`Server on ${port}`));

for (const sig of ['SIGINT', 'SIGTERM']) {
  process.on(sig, () => server.close(() => process.exit(0)));
}
```

## 9. `console.log` for Logging
Use a structured logger (`pino`, `winston`) so logs are parseable and you can redact secrets. Never log request bodies/headers blindly — they can contain tokens.

## 10. Health Endpoint Leaks Info
`/health` returns server time, which is minor but can aid fingerprinting. Consider returning just `{status:'ok'}` publicly and gating a richer `/health/detailed` behind auth.

## 11. Disable `x-powered-by`
```js
app.disable('x-powered-by'); // (helmet does this too)
```

